				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">If you've built a circuit to act as a Game Link slave (with another Game Boy as the master), I'd bet you can use it nearly unchanged with the NES. The <a href="http://nocash.emubase.de/pandocs.htm#serialdatatransferlinkcable" class="postlink">Game Link protocol</a> for Game Boy and Game Boy Color is 5.0 V <a href="http://arduino.cc/en/Reference/SPI" class="postlink">SPI</a> over a <a href="http://nocash.emubase.de/pandocs.htm#externalconnectors" class="postlink">6-pin connector</a>, and the NES controller port speaks a primitive bit-banged form of SPI as well.<br /><br />You need to handle three signals on the <a href="http://nocash.emubase.de/everynes.htm#controllerspinouts" class="postlink">NES controller port</a>:<br />MISO: D0 in (not shared)<br />MOSI: D0 out/strobe (shared between controllers)<br />SCK: Clock (not shared)<br />SS: If your SPI slave implementation requires it, it can be reconstructed from MOSI and/or SCK<br /><br />Game Boy link cables are &quot;null modem&quot;, that is, they cross MISO and MOSI.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

